Creative destruction occurs despite our best efforts to stamp it out. In a sense, disruption is an outsider to the essence of the industrial and post-industrial period of the last two centuries, the overriding philosophy of which is automation and algorithmisation aimed at efficiency and control. - Ashwin Parameswaran (2012)
%
The endogenous nature of [the] buildup of complexity eventually makes the system fundamentally illegible to the human operator - a phenomenon that is ironic given that the fundamental aim of the control revolution is to increase legibility. - Ashwin Parameswaran (2012)
%
Near-optimal robustness in both natural and economic systems is not achieved with simplistically diverse agent compositions or with significant redundancies or slack at agent level. - Ashwin Parameswaran (2012)
%
The key to achieving resilience with near-optimal configurations is to tackle disturbances and generate novelty/innovation with an an emergent systemic response that reconfigures the system rather than simply a localised response. - Ashwin Parameswaran (2012)
%
Eventually mean/median system performance deteriorates as more and more pure slack and redundancy needs to be built in at all levels to make up for the irreversibly fragile nature of the system. The business cycle is an oscillation between efficient fragility and robust inefficiency. Over the course of successive cycles, both poles of this oscillation get worse which leads to median/mean system performance falling rapidly at the same time that the tails deteriorate due to the increased illegibility of the automated system to the human operator. - Ashwin Parameswaran (2012)
%
Complex systems are intrinsically hazardous systems. - Richard I. Cook, MD. 'How Complex Systems Fail'.
%
Complex systems are heavily and successfully defended against failure. The high consequences of failure lead over time to the construction of multiple layers of defense against failure. These defenses include obvious technical components (e.g. backup systems, 'safety' features of equipment) and human components (e.g. training, knowledge) but also a variety of organizational, institutional, and regulatory defenses (e.g. policies and procedures, certification, work rules, team training). - Richard I. Cook, MD. 'How Complex Systems Fail'.
%
Catastrophe requires multiple failures. - Richard I. Cook, MD. 'How Complex Systems Fail'.
%
Complex systems contain changing mixtures of failures latent within them. - Richard I. Cook, MD. 'How Complex Systems Fail'.
%
Complex systems run in degraded mode. - Richard I. Cook, MD. 'How Complex Systems Fail'.
